SIMPLE: skirt
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Skirt
<hw>Skirt</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>skyrt</ets>,
of Scand. origin; cf. Icel. <ets>skyrta</ets> a shirt, Sw.
<ets>sk⟦oum⟧rt</ets> a skirt, <ets>skjorta</ets> a shirt. See
<er>Shirt</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The lower and loose part of a
coat, dress, or other like garment; the part below the waist; <as>as,
the <ex>skirt</ex> of a coat, a dress, or a mantle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A loose edging to any part of a dress.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A narrow lace, or a small <qex>skirt</qex> of ruffled linen, which
runs along the upper part of the stays before, and crosses the breast,
being a part of the tucker, is called the modesty piece.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Border; edge; margin; extreme part of anything</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Here in the <xex>skirts</xex> of the forest.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A petticoat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The diaphragm, or midriff, in animals.</def>
<rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skirt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Skirt
<hw>Skirt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Skirted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Skirting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover with a
skirt; to surround.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Skirted</qex> his loins and thighs with downy gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To border; to form the border or edge of; to run
along the edge of; <as>as, the plain was <ex>skirted</ex> by rows of
trees</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧When sundown <xex>skirts</xex> the moor.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skirt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Skirt
<hw>Skirt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To be on the border; to live near
the border, or extremity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Savages . . . who <qex>skirt</qex> along our western
frontiers.</q> <rj><qau>S. S. Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skirting</ent>⟦br⟧
